WEBVTT
Kind: captions
Language: en

00:00:00.000 --> 00:00:06.020
Hi, I'm John Green, this is Crash Course U.S.
History, and today, we're going to talk about slavery,
which is not funny.

00:00:06.020 --> 00:00:10.080
Yeah, so we put a lei on the eagle to
try and cheer you up, but let's face it, this
is going to be depressing.

00:00:10.080 --> 00:00:14.360
With slavery, every time you think, like,
"Aw, it couldn't have been that bad," it turns
out to have been much worse.

00:00:14.360 --> 00:00:15.920
Mr. Green, Mr. Green! But what about –

00:00:15.920 --> 00:00:19.000
Yeah, Me from the Past, I'm going to stop you right
there, because you're going to embarrass yourself.

00:00:19.000 --> 00:00:20.640
Slavery was hugely important to America.

00:00:20.640 --> 00:00:29.100
I mean, it led to a civil war and it also lasted what,
at least in U.S. history, counts as a long-ass time,
from 1619 to 1865.

00:00:29.100 --> 00:00:35.080
And yes, I know there's a 1200-year-old church
in your neighborhood in Denmark, but we're not
talking about Denmark!

00:00:35.080 --> 00:00:38.520
But slavery is most important because we still
struggle with its legacy.

00:00:38.520 --> 00:00:42.420
So, yes, today's episode will probably not
be funny, but it will be important.

00:00:42.420 --> 00:00:51.040
[Theme Music]

00:00:51.040 --> 00:00:57.220
So the slave-based economy in the South is
sometimes characterized as having been separate from
the Market Revolution, but that's not really the case.

00:00:57.220 --> 00:01:04.900
Without southern cotton, the North wouldn't have been
able to industrialize, at least not as quickly, because
cotton textiles were one of the first industrially products.

00:01:04.900 --> 00:01:11.840
And the most important commodity in world trade
by the nineteenth century, and 3/4 of the world's
cotton came from the American South.

00:01:11.840 --> 00:01:18.800
And speaking of cotton, why has no one mentioned
to me that my collar has been half popped this entire
episode, like I'm trying to recreate the Flying Nun's hat.

00:01:18.800 --> 00:01:23.060
And although there were increasingly fewer slaves
in the North as northern states outlawed slavery,

00:01:23.060 --> 00:01:26.120
cotton shipments overseas made northern
merchants rich.

00:01:26.120 --> 00:01:29.820
Northern bankers financed the purchase of
land for plantations.

00:01:29.820 --> 00:01:35.980
Northern insurance companies insured slaves
who were, after all, considered property, and
very valuable property.

00:01:35.980 --> 00:01:41.820
And in addition to turning cotton into cloth
for sale overseas, northern manufacturers
sold cloth back to the South,

00:01:41.820 --> 00:01:45.120
where it was used to clothe the very slaves
who had cultivated it.

00:01:45.120 --> 00:01:49.200
But certainly the most prominent effects of
the slave-based economy were seen in the South.

00:01:49.200 --> 00:01:56.000
The profitability of slaved-based agriculture,
especially King Cotton, meant that the South
would remain largely agricultural and rural.

00:01:56.000 --> 00:02:00.360
Slave states were home to a few cities, like
St. Louis and Baltimore, but with the exception
of New Orleans,

00:02:00.360 --> 00:02:06.260
almost all southern urbanization took place in the upper
South, further away from the large cotton plantations.

00:02:06.260 --> 00:02:11.220
And slave-based agriculture was so profitable
that it siphoned money away from other economic
endeavors.

00:02:11.220 --> 00:02:13.300
Like, there was very little industry in the
South.

00:02:13.300 --> 00:02:16.230
It produced only 10% of the nation's manufactured
goods.

00:02:16.230 --> 00:02:23.880
And, as most of the capital was being plowed into
the purchase of slaves, there was very little room for
technological innovation, like, for instance, railroads.

00:02:23.880 --> 00:02:27.760
This lack of industry and railroads would
eventually make the South suck at the Civil
War, thankfully.

00:02:27.760 --> 00:02:35.080
In short, slavery dominated the South, shaping
it both economically and culturally, and slavery
wasn't a minor aspect of American society.

00:02:35.080 --> 00:02:42.120
By 1860, there were four million slaves in
the U.S., and in the South, they made up one
third of the total population.

00:02:42.120 --> 00:02:47.320
Although in the popular imagination, most plantations
were these sprawling affairs with hundreds of slaves,

00:02:47.320 --> 00:02:51.200
in reality, the majority of slaveholders
owned five or fewer slaves.

00:02:51.200 --> 00:02:57.560
And, of course, most white people in the South owned
no slaves at all, though, if they could afford to, they
would sometimes rent slaves to help with their work.

00:02:57.560 --> 00:03:04.040
These were the so-called yeoman farmers who
lived self-sufficiently, raised their own food, and
purchased very little in the Market Economy.

00:03:04.040 --> 00:03:08.220
They worked the poorest land and, as a result,
were mostly pretty poor themselves.

00:03:08.220 --> 00:03:12.400
But even they largely supported slavery,
partly, perhaps, for aspirational reasons,

00:03:12.400 --> 00:03:18.280
and partly because the racism inherent to the system
gave even the poorest whites legal and social status.

00:03:18.280 --> 00:03:23.700
And southern intellectuals worked hard to
encourage these ideas of white solidarity
and to make the case for slavery.

00:03:23.700 --> 00:03:29.360
Many of the founders, a bunch of whom you'll remember,
held slaves, saw slavery as a necessary evil.

00:03:29.360 --> 00:03:37.280
Jefferson once wrote, quote, "As it is, we
have the wolf by the ear, and we can neither
hold him, nor safely let him go.

00:03:37.280 --> 00:03:41.380
Justice is on one scale, and self-preservation
in the other."

00:03:41.380 --> 00:03:47.740
The belief that justice and self-preservation
couldn't sit on the same side of the scale
was really opposed to the American idea,

00:03:47.740 --> 00:03:50.080
and, in the end, it would make the Civil War inevitable.

00:03:50.080 --> 00:03:55.380
But as slavery became more entrenched in
these ideas of liberty and political equality were
embraced by more people,

00:03:55.380 --> 00:03:59.520
some southerners began to make the case
that slavery wasn't just a necessary evil.

00:03:59.520 --> 00:04:03.100
They argued, for instance, that slaves benefited
from slavery.

00:04:03.100 --> 00:04:07.700
Because, you know, because their masters fed
them and clothed them and took care of them
in their old age.

00:04:07.700 --> 00:04:09.760
You still hear this argument today, astonishingly.

00:04:09.760 --> 00:04:12.340
In fact, you'll probably see asshats in the
comments saying that in the comments.

00:04:12.340 --> 00:04:15.920
I will remind you, it's not cursing if you
are referring to an actual ass.

00:04:15.920 --> 00:04:26.020
This paternalism allowed masters to see themselves
as benevolent and to contrast their family-oriented
slavery with the cold, mercenary Capitalism
of the free-labor North.

00:04:26.020 --> 00:04:33.310
So yeah, in the face of rising criticism of
slavery, some southerners began to argue that the
institution was actually good for the social order.

00:04:33.310 --> 00:04:40.540
One of the best-known proponents of this view
was John C. Calhoun, who, in 1837, said this
in a speech on the Senate floor:

00:04:40.540 --> 00:04:43.460
"I hold that, in the present state of civilization,

00:04:43.460 --> 00:04:51.360
where two races of different origin and
distinguished by color and other physical differences
as well as intellectual, are brought together,

00:04:51.360 --> 00:04:58.160
the relation now existing in the slave-holding states
between the two is, instead of an evil, a good.

00:04:58.160 --> 00:04:59.960
A positive good."

00:04:59.960 --> 00:05:04.560
Now, of course, John C. Calhoun was a fringe
politician, and nobody took his views particularly
seriously.

00:05:04.560 --> 00:05:07.520
Stan: Well, he was Secretary of State from
1844 to 1845.

00:05:07.520 --> 00:05:10.180
John: Well, I mean, who really cares about
the Secretary of State, Stan?

00:05:10.180 --> 00:05:13.580
Danica: Eh, he was also Secretary of War from
1817 to 1825.

00:05:13.580 --> 00:05:16.230
John: All right, but we don't even have a Secretary
of War anymore, so...

00:05:16.230 --> 00:05:19.300
Meredith: And he was Vice President from 1825
to 1832.

00:05:19.300 --> 00:05:21.890
John: Oh my god, were we insane?!

00:05:21.890 --> 00:05:28.620
We were, of course, but we justified the insanity
with Biblical passages and with the examples
of the Greeks and Romans,

00:05:28.620 --> 00:05:33.620
and with outright racism, arguing that black
people were inherently inferior to whites.

00:05:33.620 --> 00:05:37.560
And that not to keep them in slavery would
upset the natural order of things.

00:05:37.560 --> 00:05:41.140
A worldview popularized millennia ago by my
nemesis, Aristotle.

00:05:41.140 --> 00:05:42.490
God, I hate Aristotle.

00:05:42.490 --> 00:05:44.360
You know what defenders of Aristotle always
say?

00:05:44.360 --> 00:05:47.520
"He was the first person to identify dolphins."

00:05:47.520 --> 00:05:50.400
Well, ok, dolphin identifier.

00:05:50.400 --> 00:05:53.620
Yes, that is what he should be remembered
for, but he's a terrible philosopher!

00:05:53.620 --> 00:05:55.120
Here's the truth about slavery:

00:05:55.120 --> 00:06:00.180
It was coerced labor that relied upon intimidation
and brutality and dehumanization.

00:06:00.180 --> 00:06:03.040
And this wasn't just a cultural system, it
was a legal one.

00:06:03.040 --> 00:06:09.860
I mean, Louisiana law proclaimed that a slave
"owes his master... a respect without bounds,
and an absolute obedience."

00:06:09.860 --> 00:06:12.680
The signal feature of slaves' lives was work.

00:06:12.680 --> 00:06:20.300
I mean, conditions and tasks varied, but all
slaves labored, usually from sunup to sundown,
and almost always without any pay.

00:06:20.300 --> 00:06:25.370
Most slaves worked in agriculture on plantations,
and conditions were different, depending on
which crops are grown.

00:06:25.370 --> 00:06:29.460
Like, slaves on the rice plantations of South
Carolina had terrible working conditions,

00:06:29.460 --> 00:06:36.580
but they labored under the task system, which meant
that once they had completed their allotted daily work,
they would have time to do other things.

00:06:36.580 --> 00:06:42.960
But lest you imagine this is like how we have
work and leisure time, bear in mind that they
were owned and treated as property.

00:06:42.960 --> 00:06:49.880
On cotton plantations, most slaves worked
in gangs, usually under the control of an overseer,
or another slave who was called a "driver."

00:06:49.880 --> 00:06:55.300
This was back-breaking work done in the southern sun
and humidity, and so it's not surprising that whippings –

00:06:55.300 --> 00:06:58.880
– or the threat of them –  were often
necessary to get slaves to work.

00:06:58.880 --> 00:07:03.480
It's easy enough to talk about the brutality of slave
discipline, but it can be difficult to internalize it.

00:07:03.480 --> 00:07:09.460
Like, you look at these pictures, but because
you've seen them over and over again, they don't
have the power they once might have.

00:07:09.460 --> 00:07:14.640
The pictures can tell a story about cruelty,
but they don't necessarily communicate how
arbitrary it all was.

00:07:14.640 --> 00:07:18.700
As, for example, in this story, told by a
woman who was a slave as a young girl:

00:07:18.700 --> 00:07:22.840
"[The] overseer... went to my father one morning
and said, "Bob, I'm gonna whip you this morning."

00:07:22.840 --> 00:07:28.100
Daddy said, "I ain't done nothing," and he
said, "I know it, I'm going to whip you to
keep you from doing nothing,"

00:07:28.100 --> 00:07:33.760
and he hit him with that cowhide – you know
it would cut the blood out of you with every lick
if they hit you hard."

00:07:33.760 --> 00:07:38.880
That brutality – the whippings, the brandings,
the rape – was real, and it was intentional,

00:07:38.880 --> 00:07:43.120
because, in order for slavery to function,
slaves had to be dehumanized.

00:07:43.120 --> 00:07:51.740
This enabled slaveholders to rationalize what
they were doing, and it was hoped to reduce
slaves to the animal property that is implied
by the term "chattel slavery."

00:07:51.740 --> 00:07:57.560
So the idea was that slaveholders wouldn't
think of their slaves as human, and slaves
wouldn't think of themselves as human.

00:07:57.560 --> 00:07:59.820
But it didn't work.
Let's go to the Thought Bubble.

00:07:59.820 --> 00:08:05.300
Slaves' resistance to their dehumanization
took many forms, but the primary way was by
forming families.

00:08:05.300 --> 00:08:10.920
Family was a refuge for slaves and a source of
dignity that masters recognized and sought to stifle.

00:08:10.920 --> 00:08:15.360
A paternalistic slave owner named Bennet H. Barrow
wrote in his rules for the Highland Plantation:

00:08:15.360 --> 00:08:21.700
"No rule that I have stated is of more
importance than that relating to Negroes
marrying outside of the plantation...

00:08:21.700 --> 00:08:23.500
It creates a feeling of independence."

00:08:23.500 --> 00:08:28.520
Most slaves did marry, usually for life, and,
when possible, slaves grew up in two-parent
households.

00:08:28.520 --> 00:08:32.740
Single-parent households were common, though,
as a result of one parent being sold.

00:08:32.740 --> 00:08:40.020
In the upper South, where the economy was
shifting from tobacco to different, less labor-intensive
cash crops, the sale of slaves was common.

00:08:40.020 --> 00:08:45.040
Perhaps one-third of slave marriages in states
like Virginia were broken up by sale.

00:08:45.040 --> 00:08:47.640
Religion was also an important part of life
in slavery.

00:08:47.640 --> 00:08:52.400
While masters wanted their slaves to learn
the parts of the Bible that talked about being
happy in bondage,

00:08:52.400 --> 00:08:57.560
slave worship tended to focus on the stories of Exodus,
where Moses brought the slaves out of bondage,

00:08:57.560 --> 00:09:01.540
or Biblical heroes, who overcame great
odds, like Daniel and David.

00:09:01.540 --> 00:09:06.240
And, although most slaves were forbidden to
learn to read and write, many did anyway.

00:09:06.240 --> 00:09:07.580
And some became preachers.

00:09:07.580 --> 00:09:13.400
Slave preachers were often very charismatic
leaders, and they roused the suspicion of
slave owners, and not without reason.

00:09:13.400 --> 00:09:16.580
Two of the most important slave uprisings
in the South were led by preachers.

00:09:16.580 --> 00:09:17.740
Thanks, Thought Bubble.

00:09:17.740 --> 00:09:19.450
Oh, it's time for the Mystery Document?

