evil, and let the oppressed go free..."

00:10:06.060 --> 00:10:10.540
All right, it's definitely a preacher, because
only preachers have read Malachi.

00:10:10.540 --> 00:10:13.460
Probably African American, probably not someone
from the South.

00:10:13.460 --> 00:10:18.080
I'm going to guess that it is Richard Allen,
the founder of the African Methodist Episcopal
Church?

00:10:18.080 --> 00:10:19.920
[buzzing noise]
DAAAH, DANG IT!

00:10:19.920 --> 00:10:24.500
It's Joseph Taper, and Stan just pointed out
to me that I should have known it was Joseph
Taper because it starts out,

00:10:24.500 --> 00:10:27.280
"Since I have been in the Queen's dominions..."

00:10:27.280 --> 00:10:31.880
He was in Canada. He escaped slavery to
Canada. The Queen's dominions!

00:10:31.880 --> 00:10:36.440
All right, Canadians, I blame you for this,
although, thank you for abolishing slavery
decades before we did.

00:10:36.440 --> 00:10:37.580
[electric sounds] AHHH!

00:10:37.580 --> 00:10:42.220
So, the Mystery Document shows one of the
primary ways that slaves resisted their oppression:
by running away.

00:10:42.220 --> 00:10:47.220
Although some slaves like Joseph Taper escaped
for good by running away to northern free states,

00:10:47.220 --> 00:10:50.480
or even to Canada, where they wouldn't
have to worry about fugitive slave laws,

00:10:50.480 --> 00:10:55.820
even more slaves ran away temporarily, hiding out
in the woods or the swamps, and eventually returning.

00:10:55.820 --> 00:11:01.660
No one knows exactly how many slaves escaped
to freedom, but the best estimate is that a thousand
or so a year made the journey northward.

00:11:01.660 --> 00:11:07.680
Most fugitive slaves were young men, but the
most famous runaway has been hanging out behind
me all day long: Harriet Tubman.

00:11:07.680 --> 00:11:11.620
Harriet Tubman escaped to Philadelphia at
the age of 29, and over the course of her life,

00:11:11.620 --> 00:11:17.380
she made about 20 trips back to Maryland
to help friends and relatives make the journey
north on the Underground Railroad.

00:11:17.380 --> 00:11:22.420
But a more dramatic form of resistance to
slavery was actual, armed rebellion, which
was attempted.

00:11:22.420 --> 00:11:27.960
Now, individuals sometimes took matters into
their own hands and beat or even killed their
white overseers or masters.

00:11:27.960 --> 00:11:33.780
Like Bob, the guy who received the arbitrary
beating, responded to it by killing his overseer
with a hoe.

00:11:33.780 --> 00:11:36.800
But that said, large-scale slave uprisings
were relatively rare.

00:11:36.800 --> 00:11:41.040
The four most famous ones all took place in a
35-year period at the beginning of the 19th century.

00:11:41.040 --> 00:11:45.910
Gabriel's Rebellion in 1800 – which we've
talked about before – was discovered before
he was able to carry out his plot.

00:11:45.910 --> 00:11:52.360
Then, in 1811, a group of slaves upriver from
New Orleans seized cane, knives, and guns, and
marched on the city before militia stopped them.

00:11:52.360 --> 00:11:59.460
And in 1822, Denmark Vesey, a former slave
who had purchased his freedom, may have organized
a plot to destroy Charleston, South Carolina.

00:11:59.460 --> 00:12:05.480
I say "may have" because the evidence against him
is disputed and comes from a trial that was not fair.

00:12:05.480 --> 00:12:09.600
But regardless, the end result of that trial
was that he was executed, as were 34 slaves.

00:12:09.600 --> 00:12:15.680
But the most successful slave rebellion, at
least in the sense that they actually killed some
people, was Nat Turner's in August 1831.

00:12:15.680 --> 00:12:21.380
Turner was a preacher, and with a group of
about 80 slaves, he marched from farm to farm
in South Hampton County, Virginia,

00:12:21.380 --> 00:12:27.100
killing the inhabitants, most of whom were women
and children, because the men were attending a
religious revival meeting in North Carolina.

00:12:27.100 --> 00:12:34.560
Turner and 17 other rebels were captured and
executed, but not before they struck terror into the
hearts of whites all across the American South.

00:12:34.560 --> 00:12:42.320
Virginia's response was to make slavery worse,
passing even harsher laws that forbade slaves from
preaching, and prohibited teaching them to read.

00:12:42.320 --> 00:12:47.720
Other slave states followed Virginia's lead and, by
the 1830s, slavery had grown, if anything, more harsh.

00:12:47.720 --> 00:12:51.560
So, this shows that large-scaled armed
resistance was – Django Unchained aside –

00:12:51.560 --> 00:12:55.620
not just suicidal, but also a threat to loved
ones and, really, to all slaves.

00:12:55.620 --> 00:12:59.920
But, it is hugely important to emphasize that
slaves did resist their oppression.

00:12:59.920 --> 00:13:03.660
Sometimes this meant taking up arms, but usually
it meant more subtle forms of resistance,

00:13:03.660 --> 00:13:08.840
like intentional work slowdowns or sabotaging
equipment, or pretending not to understand instructions.

00:13:08.840 --> 00:13:16.060
And, most importantly, in the face of systematic
legal and cultural degradation, they re-affirmed
their humanity through family and through faith.

00:13:16.060 --> 00:13:17.520
Why is this so important?

00:13:17.520 --> 00:13:21.640
Because too often in America, we still talk
about slaves as if they failed to rise up,

00:13:21.640 --> 00:13:26.080
when, in fact, rising up would not have made
life better for them or for their families.

00:13:26.080 --> 00:13:34.480
The truth is, sometimes carving out an identity as a human being in a social order that is constantly seeking to dehumanize you, is the most powerful form of resistance.

00:13:34.480 --> 00:13:45.140
Refusing to become the chattel that their masters believed them to be is what made slavery untenable and the Civil War inevitable, so make no mistake, slaves fought back.

00:13:45.140 --> 00:13:48.220
And in the end, they won.
